<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A coastal species resembling 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jalapa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea jalapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differing in the more hirsute, usually 3-lobed leaves and white, usually solitary flowers as well as the distinctive habitat. It is reported to be a night-flowering moth pollinated species (Austin and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Huáman">Huaman</normalizedToken>
1996).
</paragraph>
